</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9298E66959BAEB6F8BABA23C108C2AA7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="18B8CA182672E3507F48741D8521D2F6" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD35DCD616E644F81E9F3D274C0545A0" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Somewhat resembling a large-leaved 
<taxonomicName id="C5A729308A5134938A27F65FA8F3B71D" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="indica">
<emphasis id="66B11ED58CF40EAED436C41329D48E64" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but leaves never grey-tomentose beneath, bracteoles caducous, sepals very unequal, the inner oblong, much shorter than the outer and the inflorescence not usually compact.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="428C372C2FA0D02F69B9BA08A9EFC2C5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="FE19D172E5E017566AF0588DFF587065" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="magnifolia">
<emphasis id="88FE4C1E09BA3F0C4547F68F0FC13580" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea magnifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very variable with respect to the indumentum of the sepals and the corolla, varying from subglabrous to pilose, although there is always the tendency for hairs to fall with age. 
<emphasis id="5B8043F4E93EB1A6CD8C6225709CA447" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Fuentes et al.</emphasis>
9300 (MO) is a very unusual specimen, the inflorescence is exceptionally long-pedunculate and very dense, the outer sepals are broadly oblong not lanceolate, obtuse and mucronate, not acuminate and a mere 10 mm long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
